[From obituary attached to back of image:] Died in Medford, Friday, March 9. Descendant of Mayflower stock: Miles Standish, John and Priscilla Alden and Alexander Samson. Parents were Benjamin F. and Harriet Northey Samson. Born in Medford December 7, 1840. Enlisted at Medford, Company C, 39th Massachusetts on August 25, 1862. Transferred to 10th U.S. Colored Troops and commissioned 2nd Lieutenant on October 26, 1863. Promoted 1st Lieutenant April 27, 1864 and Captain October 19, 1864. Mustered out at Galveston, Texas, May 17, 1866. Longest serving and last to return of Medford's quota. Wife Clarissa Washburn Egery died 1911. Survived by two daughters, three grandchildren, three great-grandchildren, bother and sister.

abstract_tsi: 'This is the story of a young man and Provincetown High School classmate of mine who indeed did ride a whale in Provincetown Harbor. Frank Cabral, born and raised here, was 16 years old and a junior in high school when this event happened. Frank was a quiet, studious pupil who graduated and left Provincetown to teach high school in California in 1954. While growing up here his father owned a fresh seafood store on Commercial St. and caught his fish daily in our harbor. Frank worked each summer with his father and in June 1948, which he thought was a pretty ordinary day, this event happened. Frank was in one large dory and his father was in another nearby, the whale (which Frank named Willie) came up under his dory and smashed a huge hole in it. Frank was thrown in the air and landed on the whale's back for a matter of seconds, holding on for his life. He had heavy clothing and boots on and went down, his father was able to rescue him and pull him aboard, other fisherman in the area did witness most of this happening. Needless to say Frank's classmates continued for many years to tease him about this event! He appeared on radio and had articles written in the papers and magazines about 'Willie.' Frank has since traveled all over the world with his wife and has sent us, his classmates, stories of all his adventures.'
institution_name_ssi: University of Massachusetts Boston, Joseph P. Healey Library
